T1  - A two-level electricity demand model: Evaluation of the connecticut time-of-day pricing test
AU  - Hausmann, J.A.
AU  - Kinnucan, M.
AU  - McFaddden, D.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 10
IS  - 3
SP  - 263
EP  - 289
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/08/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(79)90085-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440767990085X
AB  - A two-stage budgeting model is developed for electricity demand where comsumption in each period is treated as a different commodity. A relative household demand model is first estimated, a consistent price index for electricity is constructed, and then a total electricity consumption model is estimated. Economic procedures are derived which permit application of the model to both time-of-day price situations and also declining vlock price situatiions which result in non-linear budget sets. The model is applied to both types of situations- the data from the Connecticut time-of-day pricing test as well as data from the declining block rate situation of the prevoius year. The model is also tested in a forecasting application to time-of-day customers.
